						<div class="descElab">
							<p>
							Using an android device and 3 Onyx Beacons, we're able to track the location of the device in terms of x and y coordinates by obtaining the distance to the 3 beacons and then trilaterating the device's position. These coordinate pairs are then uploaded to the db2 database provided by bluemix, where a "heat" map can be generated. 
							</p>
							<p>The hotspots indicate where the phone has been positioned for the longest and the spots get redder the more coordinate pairs there are around the area. We made this during SportsHack14 to push forward the idea of tracking players on any given playing field to gather rich data about player, and subsequently, team behaviour during a match. 
							</p>
							<p>The data can be packaged and then marketed to teams, players and broadcast stations alike for purposes ranging from self improvement to allowing more viewers to comprehend a game deeply. 
